���L-Compact(����)
    
    Author: C. N. Apostol
    

  Cpt ���ӷ�, ���q R^n �W�}�l���_. �n�q R^n �W�}�l���_, �N�����q R �W
  �Ӭ�. �ڭ����n���D����s���Ʀb���ɳ��϶��W, ���D�`�h�ʽ�i�H�Q��:
  �Ѧp: ���ós��, �Ϊ̳s���Ƥ����ȩw�z��. �ҥH; �o�N�|���ڭ̥h�Q��
  ���� [a,b], where a and b both are finite, �W������S�����ʽ�? ���B;
  �A���ӹ�� open cover �����ͭn�P�줣���ͤ~�O. �]���A���N�����b [a,b]
  �W�� open cover, �A�@�w�i�H��o�즳���� subcover �h�\�� [a,b]. �]��;
  �ڭ̥i�H�h�w�q��� Compact.( �A�i�H�� [a,b] �@�@��, �H�ι� (a,b) �@�@
  ��, �A�N�|����M���� )
  Note: �b�w�q Compact ���e; ���M, �٥����h�w�q��� open cover.
                                                                                
  So, now let's focus the definition about compact. And hope you have the
  intuition above why the defintion comes from in order to construct your
  frame of mathematics. But I have to say something to avoid mistakes. For
  above saying, this is just a way to understand them but not only a way.

  (Def-Open cover): A open cover is a collection of open sets in (M,d).
                    And when we say F is an cover cover of S, it just means
                    S is contained in �� O_i, where O_i in F. And so called
                    finite subcover of S, it means S is contained in �� O_i,
                    where i =1, 2, .., n.
                                                                                
  (Def-Compact): Let C be a subset in (M,d). If for any open cover F of C,
                 i.e, C is contained in �� O_i, where O_i in F, we always
                 have C is contained in �� O_i, where i =1, 2, .., n. we
                 say C is cpt. So, we always say that:
                                                                                
  C: Cpt, ����N�@�Ӷ}�л\ (open cover) of C, �ڭ̳����즳���Ӥl�л\.
                                                                                
                                                                                
 (Thm): C is a Cpt in R^n iff C is closed and bounded iff An infinite
        subset of C has an accumulation point in C.
  Note: C is a Cpt in R^n iff C is closed (���w�z, �٬� Heine-Borel)
        C is a Cpt in R^n iff An infinite subset of C has an accumula-
        tion point in C.     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
        ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ This is called sequentially cpt.
                                                                                
  Note:(���D) �ХΤW���w�z���ԭz, �h�ҩ��Y {x_n} in R and x_n -> x in R.
       The set {x_1,x_2,..,x_n,..}��{x} is cpt in R. �p�G�A�`�N�I, �A�N
       �|�o�{, ���קA�ΤW���w�z�����@�ӳ���, ���u�O�����w�q����g. �}�G�a!
                                                                                
  �W�z���w�z, �b�@�몺���L�ѤW����. �ӥB�D�`���n. �]�����F Cpt, �ڭ̯�
  �����a�h�Q�צb�����ת��F��.
                                                                                
  �g�ѼƾǮa�� (Heine, Borel, Lindelof, etc) ���V�O, �ڭ̵o�{�F, �b R^n
  �W, ���N�@�Ӧ��ɥB�ʳ����l��, ���N�঳ Cpt ���ʽ�. ��O; �ڭ̷Q�h�ݦb
  �@�몺�׶q�Ŷ��W, �O�_��O���W�����w�z? ����: ���O!
                                                                                
  (Thm): C is a Cpt in (M,d) iff C is sequentially cpt. (���w�z, �]��
         Bolzano-Weiertrass �w�z)
  Note: In general, we cannot conclude that C is cpt from C is closed
        and bounded. Ex: �����׶q�Ŷ� (�Ϊ̤����ƪ��Ŷ�).
                                      ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^(*)
  For (*): A cpt set C in (M,d) => C is complete when regarded C as a
           metric subspace of M. And in general, we have the theorem:
          A cpt set C in (M,d) iff C is complete and totally bounded.
  Q: ���� totally bounded ���󤣹�? A: �Ҽ{ Hilbert space.
                                                                                
  (Applications): f:(M,d)->(N,d')
  1: f is continous on C, where C is cpt in (M,d), then f(C): cpt.
  2: f is continous on C, where C is cpt in (M,d), then f is uniformly
    continous on C.
  3: Form 1, we can have IVT when adds to the concept of connceted.
  More..


